[2] The speaker explores the psychological impact of makeup on individuals, particularly focusing on self-esteem and confidence. Makeup is not just a tool for enhancing physical appearance but also plays a significant role in how people perceive themselves and interact with the world. For many, especially women, wearing makeup can boost self-confidence, help with social interactions, and provide a sense of control over how they are seen by others. However, the pressure to wear makeup and meet societal beauty standards can also lead to feelings of insecurity and anxiety. The speaker emphasizes the importance of understanding how makeup influences mental health, suggesting that while it can have positive effects on self-image, its crucial to maintain a balanced perspective and not overly depend on it. Ultimately, makeup serves as both a tool for empowerment and a potential source of psychological stress.

Nowadays, people can easily access celebrities and models, so they lose their self confidence and try to hide who they are. I really feel this tendency. I hope more and more people will have confidence in themselves and keep their own beauty. It can lead to make-up being a more enjoyable thing for all people.

However, I strongly dislike the idea of feeling forced to wear it every single day. The pressure from society or from others to always look a certain way is something I feel uncomfortable with. I believe everyone should have the freedom to choose when and how they use makeup, based on their own feelings, not outside expectations.
